The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", as published in a pamphlet
Women considered witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are usually elderly, unable to work, for example, for health reasons, are single and have no children.
Women who "return" witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the village.
"Men seldom suffer like that."
“Healthy young women are also not isolated, because they help with work and have children,” explains a nun who, in the state capital of West Africa, Burkina Faso, is occupying a special residence of more than one hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual "social measure".
He issued an information leaflet that should help prevent witch hunts.
However, this has a stick.
“More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso do not know how to read,” warns Die Standard newspaper about the disadvantages of written awareness.
Accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, neighbouring Burkina Faso, 72-year-old Ammy Hemmah died last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to an unfortunate set of circumstances.
According to her version, the woman got caught in the oil that is used for ritual anointings.
It was set on fire when the group wanted to "throw out the evil spirits" from the woman.
Isolation of "witches" is supported by people of all levels of education.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso: “The devourers of human souls have always posed a danger,” he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to appease the witch hunt, in Gambia last year the president still participated in it.
Gambian President Jammeh, following the death of his aunt, launched a wide-ranging witch hunt that had allegedly been linked to his death and had attempted to kill the president himself by black magic.
“To help him, he brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president’s personal escort, forcibly took randomly chosen men and women from the Gambian peoples to the President’s property in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in its report.
At the farm, the arrested people had to drink a bunch of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that also caused them intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the detainees did not survive the stay on the estate.
After international pressure, they finally released about a thousand people arrested.
The tenant of Bakala: is heated with coal stoves and signs a higher rent
The man, aged and old, crossed the doors of the customer service center of the RPG Byty company of the "coal magnate" Zde<0xC5><0x88>ek Bakala, the largest private owner of flats for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he was carrying documents with the new three-story rental contracts: his own, his daughter’s and his son’s, who is serving a sentence.
All three have just caught up in the liberalization of rents.
Instead of 3,500 Czech crowns a month, the child will pay 4,100 crowns from next year for a two-room apartment with separate second-class kitchen.
"In addition, it does not have hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," shows the man with his finger in his son's new contract, on whose signature he has full powers.
"But I signed it," he explains half angry, half resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which called the new rental conditions "incorrect and indecent", recommends that tenants not sign the new contracts and wait until December 7, when it will publish a guide informing about how to proceed in these cases.
But, before this, man only makes an ademan.
"Everybody says one thing," he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a great test laboratory for liberalization.
After New Year will happen with the vast majority of the flats that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated rent.
That's why Aktualj.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG mining waiting room is one of the four in Ostrava and, on Tuesday at nine, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are security guards and next to them a number picking machine.
"Rent 2011", you can read on a bright button on your touch screen.
When you press it, a piece of paper with a number comes out of the machine.
There is almost no time to read "157" and the number already appears on the large screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in line.
Shortly after, an older marriage arrives to ask, but the crowd in the room is not here for the new rentals.
Most people come to solve common problems, such as in the past: requests for settlements, insurance issues and similar issues.
The letters with the new rental contracts will arrive in Ostrava in the mailboxes of the tenants of most of the 44,000 floors belonging to RPG around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes on the cards a rent increase of between 15 and 38%.
On November 18, a special window opens in the customer service center for the new rentals.
“It’s been running for a week, so it’s starting,” the workers, after briefly doubting it, respond when the client presents himself as a journalist.
Liberalization and Bakala’s former mining flats are the most sensitive issues in the area.
Before the elections, the Deputy Speaker of the Parliament from Ostrava, Lubom<0xC3><0xAD>r Zaor<0xC3><0xA1>lek, of the <0xC4><0x8C>SSD, already treated them loud and clear, and now they appear continuously in the newspapers of the area.
“Twenty years later, I want a new floor.”
"I didn't even change the damn bathroom dish," the man mentioned in the introduction unravels.
According to the workers, at the moment they come more than anything retirees to check if they receive a discount on the rent if they sign on time, as promised by the special offer of RPG.
The remaining tenants who sign the new contract before December 15 will also receive half the discount on the February rental.
However, the window of mining "liberalization" certainly fails to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
“Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, they only asked about the rental in 2011 about forty or fifty people,” the employee of the window estimates.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and on its boards to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the two parties do not reach an agreement on the rental, the matter must be settled by an independent judge.
“This is not a threat, but information about the only possible way to proceed and fully comply with the law,” RPG warns on its pages.
“No one is going to be judged here,” says one of Byty’s RPG employees, and a man standing on the street in front of the customer service center gives her, at least in part, the reason.
“I get a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left for food; I don’t have the means to go to court,” he says.
But immediately, the employee sows the doubt.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaoralek warns them in the media not to sign, so maybe people will wait," he said.
Rental regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic in early 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
“Current rents still do not even cover the amounts needed to maintain the community fund,” recalls Pavel Klime<0xC5><0xA1>, director of the residential portfolio of the RPG Byty company, adding that the careless state of the community fund that angers tenants is, for the owners, the main reason for increasing rent.
While in the five years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest with rents in apartments four billion, in the four years that will go from 2011 to 2014, the figure will increase to 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling, in front of the seats in the waiting room, now repeats some data that highlights in red.
"The increase in rent in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of RPG properties."
"In addition, it will always be a maximum of 7.50 Czech crowns per square meter per month," it said on the screen.
Only increased by 38% the rental of 400 floors of the RPG portfolio.
"In such cases, this is an increase from extremely low amounts, of 19.66 crowns per square meter," says RPG.
At 2,600 floors, the rent will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that the liberalization will not suddenly affect rents, but will scale between four to eight years.
In addition, it adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the rent rise (see graph) back into the floors, mainly in heating savings: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to those who sign the rental agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need daycare
The administrative building Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say that it also hides inside a small nursery with all the same to such facilities: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design employees can come to it.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, from whose studio came out numerous well-known buildings in Brno, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-kindergarten.
The company employs around 90 people, mainly at the age of the baby boom and they wanted to allow the architects and outliners to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility to enjoy a reduced schedule, the daycare is one of the benefits that Arch.Design offers to its workers as part of its social program.
Builders and architects thus have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with the care of children.
The mini-kindergarten was an idea of Arch.Designu’s own employees and, with the support of the management, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company’s mini-kindergarten is financed through the European Social Fund under the Human Resources and Employment Operational Programme, as well as from the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding granted (a grant of more than 2.8 million Czech crowns) they were able to buy the equipment and, after two years, to hire qualified personnel and services.
When the funding runs out (two years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to keep the mini-kindergarten running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted a year and in the submission of the application for financing contributed the company Economy Rating.
The care of children is in the hands of qualified staff, and a nurse and teacher from the Ministry of Education are present for their care throughout the day. The daycare centre currently houses children with no age limit, although most of them are under three years old.
Since it is a "mini-kindergarten", it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible to adapt to the needs of parents and the children of all workers have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the contents of the mini-kindergarten program are comparable to the usual pre-school curriculum.
In it, children not only play, but also receive quality teaching: from basic learning to preparation for school, they teach to English.
The class not only has toys and board games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself create a friendly and positive atmosphere.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up school children late when they are away from their workplace.
Parents are more productive while they work.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design ranks among the firms that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, in short, this program strengthened the marketing of personnel.
The House of Bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Observe the interiors of Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs resemble the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Because of its skeleton-like shape, the locals nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Its organic forms, its striking colors, the novel use of the stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade reminiscent of the scales and the ubiquitous gently curved lines, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
The cover of the house plays with dreamy lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and wildlife.
Paying more attention, one observes a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought-out order.
At night, the whole facade of the house looks even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Snake and the twist of the shapes continues to surprise us also inside.
The corrugated wood copies the window frames, railings, door ornaments, lookouts and signs.
The Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, located in the Eixample district at number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Gr<0xC3><0xA0>cia, arose from the remodeling of a house from the year 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, initially insisted on demolishing the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s idea of making a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, consisting of several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> alone.
The architect Josep Mar<0xC3><0xAD>a Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in their project plans ornaments appeared for the apartment representative of the owner of the property and the mosaics used on the facade.
Other creators and artists also work on the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade.
The collaboration in the proposals of the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> was the beginning of the successful collaboration of Jujol with Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Mil<0xC3><0xA1> and Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s Güell Park, in which other pieces of the same are found.
Due to its organic form, the locals soon after its completion dubbed it "the house of bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows began to call it "the house of yawnings".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, appears the sword of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious motives.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> designed in the house a unique system for the central heating season with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
It can be strange its inclination of forty-five degrees.
During construction, Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> did not respect at all the rules of construction of the moment and did not let himself be influenced by them.
Nevertheless, the construction obtained the corresponding permit from the beginning, although evidently in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the city council was so shocked by the result that it asked for it to be corrected.
It bothered him, for example, that the construction included columns even up to the public sidewalk.
Arrangements were never made, quite the opposite: just fifteen days after the city council’s request, Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3> applied (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The six-story house is completely traversed by a staircase leading up to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> also worked with the modern concept of connecting space.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the living rooms and a larger group can communicate in this way without problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>, not only obtained a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> plays with light, white and blue tiles that cover the inner courtyard and skylights.
The game with the two colors brings maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb the sun's rays.
Anyone can visit the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and most recharged apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that this is a very beneficial business and extended the visits to the common area and the attic, including the roof terrace.
The price of admission to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get a 20% discount.
The amount exceeds considerably the price of entry of other buildings of Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> in the city.
If you want to enjoy the true ambience of the bed with its lizard towers, you should quickly make friends with some resident of the neighboring houses and visit them at home.
How to choose a mattress and bedside table: women and men look for different things
Nothing of a pompous frame for the bed; what really imparts its quality to a good bed is the lying surface, i.e. the mattress and the bedside table.
First of all, they must be perfectly complemented in order to adapt to specific users.
During the choice, numerous elements come into play, including the owner’s weight, height, state of health and sex.
It is also important the type of interior on which the mattress and the bedside table are located.
A typical example?
For example, in a weekend cabin that usually does not have heating, latex mattresses should not be used because they "heat" more slowly.
In addition, they usually weigh considerably more than the usual polyurethane mattresses.
Therefore, it is necessary to turn them more often.
If the canals of the center are not properly aerated and, on top of them, are on a firm basis, they keep moisture inside.
When it comes to choosing a bed, habits also influence.
Those who have spent a lot of time abroad often use a very high mattress with a soft coat and will have trouble feeling good on a lower, harder surface.
“Almost all the hockey players who came back from the NHL were complaining that they weren’t sleeping as well here.”
"For their crushed shoulders, heels and hips needed mattresses with a soft viscoelastic layer."
"These types of mattresses are also recommended for people with diabetes who have problems with the nervous system, so they receive poor information from the joints and skin," explains Sylva Hadamczikov<0xC3><0xA1>, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
Many hockey players, like other customers, have long preferred viscoelastic mattresses.
"Today there is no problem, because they have these suitable Tempur and the Italians Magniflex, but also the Czech brand Tropico."
You no longer have to be an NHL player to appreciate viscoelasticity.
This "miracle" works in a very simple way.
It optimizes its rigidity and shape depending on the heat absorbed or adapts to your body heat.
Nothing puts pressure on him; during the night, he won’t turn around like after a hard game.
He just sleeps better.
Viscoelasticity also acts as a protection against sores.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add to its height the length of your feet, that is, between 21 and 34 cm.
A man or woman with a height of about 180 cm will need a bed of between 210 and 220 cm.
The minimum width for a person should be, in a double room, 90 cm, in total 180 cm.
In the case of single rooms, for example singles, it is recommended to be between 120 and 140 cm.
So that a possible visit is also comfortable.
"If not, you can apply a simple rule to calculate the width: when lying face up, you should have your hands comfortably shrunk to the elbows," advises the engineer Helena Prokopov<0xC3><0xA1>, expert of Cechu <0xC4><0x8D>aloun<0xC3><0xAD>k<0xC5><0xAF> to decorators, who has for many years been dealing with the problematic of healthy sleep and ergonomics in the furniture.
In the double rooms, everyone needs their own mattress and mattress, so during the purchase it is necessary to pay attention to combine the height of the mattresses.
Otherwise, it will be necessary to mount the bedspreads at different heights, which is not always possible on all beds.
Foam mattresses should have a minimum height of 14 cm, models with spring interior a minimum of 15 cm, of which at least three centimeters are for the layer that adapts to the shapes and smoothness.
"When you touch it with your hand or when you settle on the mattress, you should definitely not notice the springs," warns Helena Prokopov<0xC3><0xA1>.
Each mattress requires a certain type of mattress.
The fully padded bedrooms, in which the mattress and base are like Siamese, make no sense in the bedroom.
Mattresses breathe badly and you can’t wash your cover, which is often done today.
And, since every night we sweat between 0.2 and 0.75 l of sweat, it is clear that after about five or seven years the mattress will start to remind us of a large (and congested) sieve.
For this reason, specialists reject slogans that speak of a mattress life of up to 25 years or even a lifetime warranty.
However, everything has a but.
Therefore, the sellers give a tip: on mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, carefully take care of the cleaning and washing of the cover, but it is better to add a mattress protector that can be easily removed and washed.
Although mattress covers with zipper closure are currently manufactured throughout their perimeter, so when opened they are left in two parts (something very important for washing and the size of the washing machine!), their handling in larger models (and by a single person) when lifting the mattress can seem like a fight between a fly weight and a heavy weight.
In bed, instead of a bedside table, do you have a firm board?
Never, ever!
At the very least for beds designed to spend one night visiting.
However, it should make (if you don't already have them) ventilation holes in the board and should be used with a mattress with springs inside and a minimum height of 15 cm with springs in bags (such as the German Taschenfederkern) and a soft layer.
Polyurethane mattresses should not be used on such bases.
For non-articulate sheet mattresses containing between 14 and 18 sheets, latex mattresses or sandwich mattresses (e.g., a combination of latex and coconut fiber) can be used, although a mattress with a higher number of sheets, 28 or more, in which the sheets of the lumbar region can be reinforced and reinforced is always better.
Articulated sheet slats should not be used with a spring mattress, as it does not react to reclining.
In addition to adjusting the rigidity of the sheets, shoulder protection can also be used.
It is a special fastening of the sheets that allows you to press or even tilt the sheets in such a way that they "round" the shoulders perfectly during sleep.
For men who have very wide shoulders, this is something very important.
They are even remembered by mattress manufacturers who, in the "males", began to use a softer area just around the shoulders.
They also remember women, for whom they put a softer area around the hips.
For the most demanding customers, there are cross-structured or tiled sockets with the so-called multi-torsion damping.
The pressure is distributed between different points and the tension is lowered.
You should also keep in mind that, even if you use the proper mattress and bedside table, if you use a bad pillow (large and "soft"), most of the advantages will disappear.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow must hold the head and the corners can only reach to the shoulders, so that the muscles of the same can be relaxed.
The recommended size is 50 x 60 cm, which is normal in Scandinavia, for example.
When lying on the side, the pillow should be at the same level (when combined with the shoulder-reinforced mat or the softer area of the mattress) as the height of the shoulders.
Modern mattresses seem to have something to do with the original straw-filled mattresses.
Manufacturers continue to use, increasingly, natural materials or, at least, mixtures.
In fact, biological mattresses are fashionable.
The petroleum-based raw materials, with which the polyurethane foam is made, are filled with natural oils, for example castor or soybean.
In fact, virtually all known manufacturers use soybeans.
"Biologically, in the case of mattresses, it means that the center is made only of materials of natural origin," explains Petr Va<0xC5><0xA1><0xC3><0xAD><0xC4><0x8D>ek of the company Tropico Plus.
Also, natural substances are used during the manufacture of the mattress cover, one of the first aloe vera.
But you can also opt for microcapsules, which release a fresh aroma to forest or lavender.
There are also differences for men and women.
While men "refresh" themselves with vegetable extracts from the breeze, so that the mattress cover absorbs heat and cools the body, women prefer to "heat" the cover.
Red pepper extract improves blood circulation, so women feel more warmth.
Favorites at the moment?
Mattresses made of cold foam, which are more porous, with an adapted cell structure, which makes them more permeable than those of normal polyurethane and offer more permeability.
The combination of various cold foam and viscoelastic stiffness allows you to make mattresses from various areas that know perfectly where the head, shoulders and heels are going.
A good quality mattress will cost you 7,000 crowns up.
Those who perform a therapeutic function usually have a lower VAT, since they are considered as health means.
The first to gain this advantage in the Czech Republic was Gumotex.
It is difficult to save on mattresses and mattresses.
Sometimes you can approve the offers of the manufacturers or sellers, who sometimes offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers Duofreeze mattresses with a Memory foam attached to the cover for 11,990 crowns.
The second one is available for free.
The era of viscoelasticity with an open cellular structure and high density began with Tempur's "cosmic" material.
It initially emerged as material for NASA, because during takeoffs the astronauts were subjected to a huge overload.
Tempur softens with heat and hardens with cold.
Therefore, the human body, warm, exerts a perfect effect and optimally adapts its pressure.
Therefore, it is ideal to prevent sores from occurring, but also to improve comfort during sleep.
