More and more parents are using people tracking devices to monitor their children
The fear of children is driving more and more people to think about controlling them by GPS.
The system, initially designed for vehicle tracking, can also track the movement of people and contribute in this way, for example, in the case of the disappearance of the nine-year-old girl Ani<0xC4><0x8D>ka Janatkov<0xC3><0xA1>.
At the moment the device is about the size of a matchbox, but will soon be reduced to the size of a watch.
Many people were frightened by the case of the missing Ani<0xC4><0x8D>ka and began to report on the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading your privacy.
“We’re all trying to tell ourselves that it’s not about spying, but another way to reduce the chances of a tragedy,” says Petr Pilin of the company Macro Weil, one of the providers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
“I recognize that, in certain cases, such devices can be abused, for example if they get into someone’s pocket without their knowledge, but we have not yet encountered such cases.”
“Most customers actually buy it for security reasons,” Pilin adds.
In their opinion, children should always know what the "box" is for and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bo<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1> warns about the fact that, if the child does not want to carry it, he will simply throw it away.
“Even the youngest children show great creativity when it comes to intentionally losing certain things if they want to keep them from being controlled.”
“In the past, parents relied heavily on mobile phones, but these could be turned off as easily as the tracking device,” Bo<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1> says.
In his opinion, it is questionable whether in the event of an attack such a device is really useful.
"If it's a premeditated kidnapping, the perpetrator will almost always check if the child is wearing any kind of electronic device that can reveal their location."
“Now it’s the phone.”
"As the use of tracking devices expands, it will also look for them, since their sale will certainly be carried out with a lot of advertising."
“In such cases, criminals always go one step ahead of the police,” says the psychologist.
However, he adds that such devices can help in the event of an improvised attack from a pedophile.
According to Robert <0xC4><0x8C>ech of the company RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both vehicles and people, even if, after an attack, the tracking device is immediately destroyed, its presence can help.
"The device can be configured to send the position regularly after a certain period."
"If it suffers damage, it will at least facilitate the last position of the person in question."
“The most expensive devices carry an integrated tilt meter, so if the person simply slips and stays motionless, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question,” says <0xC4><0x8C>ech.
In his opinion, such a service can be obtained even with smartphones with navigation, in which only special software must be installed.
The problem with current tracking units is that at the moment they are devices with a size similar to a matchbox or smaller mobile phones.
Therefore, they can be lost.
According to Pilin de Macro Weil, for this reason, tests are currently being carried out with devices that look like a digital clock.
“In addition, they will have the added advantage that a potential attacker may not identify the device.”
“Or identify him after a certain amount of time, which can make the police time-saving,” he adds.
Although the tracking devices are worn on the wrist or hanging, they will continue to use the same technology used for vehicle tracking.
This is the verification of the position with a GPS system (used in the usual navigation in the car) combined with the function of a mobile phone that communicates the current position.
The army has enough wicks to encircle the whole Czech Republic, but they only last two years.
The Czech army bought 445 kilometers of wick to seize explosives.
Last year, the Ministry of Defense added 224 kilometers of wick to its arsenal.
Therefore, they have stocks for 225 years.
The problem is that the life of the wick is two years, four at most.
The army bought the explosive wick from STV Group, a. s. for forty million crowns.
The General’s staff responded to MF DNES justifying the purchase of such a huge amount of wick saying soldiers need 60 kilometers of wick a year for training maneuvers.
According to the calculations of the army's pyrotechnicians, with whom MF DNES was contacted, it is decided, however, that, in such a case, such maneuvers should be carried out with frequent use of explosives every year also all generals, senior officers, and even secretaries and cleaners.
They did not want either Defense Minister Alexandr Vondr and Army Captain Vlastimil Picek exempt.
Only in this way could it be justified for the army to expend sixty kilometers of wick.
This is equivalent to 25,000 explosions.
Even if it were, the army would have enough stock for more than ten years.
If, on the contrary, for the initial training of each new professional comes with a maximum of two meters of wick, the army would have with the new purchase (even adding the consumption of the units of engineers or special) sufficient stocks for the 225 indicated above.
The soldiers of the rapid intervention brigade complained personally recently to Minister Vondra because they say they barely have ammunition for various weapons, so even the shooting practices for money are limited.
And let's not talk about the lack of underwear.
"I also fail to understand that we are repeatedly bought such amounts of wick."
"But it's their decision and they'll know why they're acting like this."
"For us, the army is a good customer that we as a company try to satisfy," admits Jan D<0xC4><0x9B>ck<0xC3><0xBD>, commercial director of STV Group.
Defense Ministry spokesman Jan Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek defends the hundreds of miles of wick, also saying he will have stockpiles of this “munition” for at least ten years.
However, Jan D<0xC4><0x9B>ck<0xC3><0xBD>, of STV Group, indicates that the wick only has a lifespan of four years and, in the case of pyrotechnic products for the army or the police, of two years.
"If stored in perfect conditions, it can last up to four," says one of the soldiers who, due to possible criticism from the army, does not want to give his name.
After the end of its life, each ammunition must be carefully checked to see if it remains reliable and will not harm the soldiers.
But these tests are not free and require additional investment.
Another argument of the Ministry is that, by buying 445 kilometers of wick, it obtained a discount.
“It cost us 60% less than last year’s order of 244 kilometers,” said Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek, a spokesman for the Ministry of Defense’s shopping center.
Just to compare: the annual wick consumption of police pyrotechnicians, who remove World War II ammunition or that left by the Soviet army, has not exceeded 1,500 meters for years.
In addition, the police always ask only the right amount to deplete the ammunition before its useful life ends.
This was decided for safety reasons for pyrotechnicians and in the meantime more modern and reliable wick types can be obtained.
The Ministry already has clear difficulties in finishing tens of thousands of tons of ammunition from the time of the Warsaw Pact, when the Czechoslovak army of two hundred thousand people was preparing for a campaign in the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnicians with whom MF DNES spoke, after a couple of years the following problem will occur with the current one: it will have to eliminate hundreds of kilometers of old wick, which is now buying "cheap".
