“When they manage to get a bottle of their father out of the closet, it can be whiskey, but it’s usually Fernet and vodka.”
“Wodka has the advantage of being lightened with juice and not smelling as much,” he explains.
This is also confirmed by the spokeswoman of Motol University Hospital, Eva Jurinov<0xC3><0xA1>.
"Normally, it's Fernet or rum."
"These are modern alcoholic beverages, particularly among schoolchildren."
“In some cases, they use cigarette butts that they picked up at home,” Jurinov<0xC3><0xA1> adds.
According to Chief Pelik<0xC3><0xA1>n, 13- and 14-year-old drinkers often appear in hospitals.
