Four girls who barely spent their teenage years wearing identical white gloves and olive green jackets and tight pants to get attention.
Four pairs of black shoes perfectly aligned.
Four elegant hats placed perfectly above the hair tied with blue and white striped bows.
“Personally, I think they look normal,” Mr. Tang said, disdainfully.
“The models are beautiful.”
More than one government has tried to clean up the image of China’s urban inspectors.
One city ordered all new recruits to have a degree.
Guangdong Province changed the grayish green color of the uniforms to a supposedly more attractive blue.
Wuhan, in central China, replaced the use of force with intimidating gazes: In 2009, according to a report, 50 officers surrounded a crumbling snack cart, and watched it with the eyebrows constantly crumbling for half an hour, until the street vendor picked up his stuff and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 inhabitants in Chengdu, has chosen a radical change of image.
Since 2003, the district has added 13 women to its urban police force, expressly elected for their appearance, proportion and youth.
The idea is to give the cowardly cop a softer, feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson would have to fight to increase China’s little respect for these city squads.
And for good reason, critics would argue.
Unlike the police, these officers are only authorized to enforce city ordinances, imposing fines and other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese news media routinely portrays a different reality.
In January 2008, Hubei Province inspectors beat a passerby to death after he used his cell phone to film them while dissolving a protest against a landfill.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing inspectors was stolen and published on the internet, describing how to effectively whip criminals without causing them to bleed.
This year, a traveling watermelon salesman in Shanghai suffered brain damage after a row with five officers.
A violent video game, available for download online, features Chinese-trained inspectors attacking street vendors.
“Chengguan has left a scar in the government,” lamented China Daily, a national publication, last year after another controversy over tactics.
The newspaper called for “really meticulous cleaning.”
Skeptics say the current approach is far from this.
