But Mr. Hayes’ lawyers have filed papers in court outlining the arguments for appeals that will likely occupy the courts for years.
One of the most provocative claims that intense reports about the process, including the widespread use of Twitter by mass media journalists, created “an atmosphere of circus,” and such widespread and immediate saturation with exhilarating details made public passions exert an inappropriate influence on the jury.
The claim could force appellate judges to deal with the question of whether the new technology requires new rules in the courtroom.
