In a surprise victory for President Obama’s campaign to protect nuclear material around the world, the Belarusian government announced Wednesday that it will relinquish its stockpile of highly enriched uranium, a critical component of nuclear weapons.
The deal was revealed in a joint statement released after Foreign Minister Hillary Rodham Clinton met with Belarusian Foreign Minister Sergei Martynov on the sidelines of a security summit.
For years, the U.S. government had been trying to persuade Belarus to give up its highly enriched uranium and appeared to have reached a point of no return last spring.
But U.S. officials told the Washington Post that a pair of classified operations with Belarus had been carried out in the past two months to remove 84.82 kg of uranium qualified for weapons from a Belarusian research facility.
This paved the way for Wednesday's deal to remove the rest of the material, about 227 kg, according to an official, who spoke from anonymity due to the confidentiality of the matter.
The deal appeared to be one of the most important outcomes of the 47-nation nuclear security summit chaired by Obama in April, which excluded Belarus.
