Sports and Law Fraud
Tretas like those of Alonso and Ramos before Ajax show ingenuity but not the will to escape a sanction.
The alleged expulsion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the match played on November 23 against Ajax in the Champions League has caused ink to be written about whether such behavior is anti-sporting and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, in the absence of a few minutes to finish the game (which his team had already clearly won), the two players deliberately lost time in making several fouls to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
That way, and since Real Madrid will end up as the leader of their group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction the next game of the league, against Auxerre, and will be able to pass clean cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA discipline committee has sanctioned the team’s coach José Mourinho with two games and different financial amounts to the players involved.
Provoking a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that arose in the case reported is due to the fact that it has been starred by a team of the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem boasts of nobility and honor, and which in past times has fined its players for similar acts) and to the orchestrated dramatization, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds a more technical episode to his dilated history.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behavior not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions commit fraud; indeed, they are actions respectful of the sport regulation, but they seem to circumvent its meaning.
The question arises from examining the type of damage they cause to the sports spirit.
One of the goods that the sporting spirit understands is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions was not put in jeopardy, that is, there was no violent game.
Another of these assets referred to with fair play is to prevent the team of the offending players from unfairly taking advantage of the opposing team, which also did not happen.
Now, the paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that they did not accommodate to what we normally characterize as cheating or law fraud, since their violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid the penalty, but precisely their action tried to be the most obvious in order to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders gain in the intentional faults examined.
Here it seems necessary to establish that the opponent is not placed in a disadvantageous situation or gains in the same game, since obviously the result of the action means leaving the team with fewer players.
Nor is it a useful strategy for the next game, as the club will not be able to count on those players.
The advantage, of course, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the team can be eliminated at the first changes, and in addition with this performance the players meet a penalty match and move to the second round of cards, in which the suspension for card accumulation occurs with one less than in the first round.
So, going through rounds, it is not so clear that it is an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against the sporting spirit, of which it is part to make strategic decisions that favor the maximum benefit from what the rules allow.
In the case we are concerned with, the players did not act to evade the application of the sanction (this would be a clear case of fraud of the law), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without bypassing the punishment or fleeing from it.
Although the line between ingenuity and fraud is blurred, this time I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises from two factors: because it was two self-expulsions and the way in which the transmission of the directive to provoke them was carried out.
The harm caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
