China maintains targets to reduce greenhouse gases
The representative of that country at COP16 said that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce the carbon footprint and detailed that it supports its offer to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020.
China maintains its offer to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, said Su Wei, the country’s representative at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th Conference of the Parties to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (COP16), Su Wei said that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce its carbon footprint and to reconvert its industry.
In fact, he said, his country has invested $245 million over the past four years in efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
However, it made clear that China will not change its objectives, but will continue to work together with the international community on this issue.
He noted that China’s climate change strategy is divided into four headings: dialogue; capacity building; institution building; and support for pilot programs.
In all these areas, progress has been made, including the approval, last year, of a new Energy Law, which includes the objectives set as regards the reduction of gas emissions, he explained.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China, federal authorities have been working in coordination with state and local authorities, to achieve the goals of energy saving, energy efficiency and emission reduction.
In addition, it abounded, are in progress or have already concluded various multi-annual plans, both funded by the Chinese government, and by governments of other countries.
For example, he referred to the Energy Efficient Use Programme, which was implemented over the past five years and which received investments from the United Nations (UN), government and private initiative.
A provincial climate change project is also underway, another for the change of incandescent spotlights to savers and one more for mitigation and adaptation, he said.
At the same table, Martin Krol, the country’s government’s scientific advisor on climate change, said China’s efforts have been greater than generally thought.
For example, he explained, per capita emissions of greenhouse gases in China are six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons; China is responsible for 9 percent of the historical contribution to pollution.
It has also made unprecedented efforts in energy use, such as increasing energy efficiency by 20 percent in the last five years and plans to do another both by 2020.
