A Global Plan to Renew Lighting
The United Nations has proposed in Cancun a plan to renew domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to reduce greenhouse gases (GHGs) by an amount that corresponds to almost one-third of the additional decrease that must be carried out to stabilize the planet’s climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is part of the set of major concrete projects that the UN hopes will be adopted in Canc<0xC3><0xBA>n to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs, which still monopolize between 50 and 70% of the market, were replaced by fluocompact bulbs or, even better, by electroluminescent diode bulbs (DEL or "LED"), much of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GHG emitted to the planet would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
It is equivalent to 70% of the emissions of the planetary automotive fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitting countries such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that were to reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt of that amount should be further reduced to stabilize, before 2020, the rise in temperatures by two degrees centigrade to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluorescent bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, energy consumption is further reduced by two times.
Fluocompact bulbs last on average between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, like those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a incandescent bulb, allowing us to get an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would apply in a hundred countries.
These new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit very little heat.
On top of that, they don't contain any mercury.
A number of experts have expressed their reservations regarding fluorescent light bulbs, as they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers put instructions.
However, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet are not fluo-compact bulbs, but coal-fired thermal power plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce electricity that is wasted from incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury a year.
The report details the benefits that this international programme would offer to each country.
For example, Indonesia would thus save $1 billion a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost it 2.5 billion.
