The top secret information about Berlusconi sent by the U.S. Embassy from Rome to the State Department was the same as Newsweek published the previous week.
So why have the revelations of these files caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, that is, that embassies, at least since World War II and since the Heads of State can call by phone or take the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some limited exercises of representation, have become centers of espionage.
Any viewer who sees research films knows it perfectly, we just seem that we don’t know it out of hypocrisy.
In any case, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can consult the most secretive country in the world’s most powerful country significantly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the "deceivers".
But let us enter into the true nature of what has happened.
Formerly, in Orwell's time, he could be conceived of in every way as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy has come true since, being able to control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it is now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the avenger of citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that can no longer even keep its own secrets endure?
It is true, as Georg Simmel said, that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, no secret, since it comes from the public realm; but to reveal, as has been done by WikiLeaks, that all secrets are meant by Clinton.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and much, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound inflicted on such a powerful power?
It is obvious that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put on the network any confidential information, since it would be like publishing it on a poster in the middle of the street.
But it’s also clear that with current technologies, you can’t expect to have confidential conversations over the phone.
Nothing is easier than figuring out if and when a Head of State has moved by plane and contacted one of his counterparts.
How will they be able to maintain private and confidential relationships in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the time being, my prediction is a matter of science fiction and therefore novel, but I imagine government agents who move discreetly in diligences with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned from memory or, at most, hiding some data written on the heels of their shoes.
That information is then stored, in a single copy, in locked drawers: ultimately, the Watergate spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology is currently advancing like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a wired telegraph (telephone).
The (analog) videotapes had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, moving forward and backward, uncovering all the secrets of editing, while now the (digital) CDs only allow you to move forward or backward from chapter to chapter, that is, to enormous proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the travel it entails, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary that politics and communication techniques bring us back to horse cars.
One last comment.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was secretly going on in the embassies.
At present, it is the embassies that request confidential information from the press.
Climate: France’s dips in its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the fast-start or early funding promises made by developed countries have been respected.
And the French hoodies have been unveiled.
Under the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union committed <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion over three years and France <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.26 billion (i.e. <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put on the table its best letters to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start funding is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation was appreciable and appreciated for what it really is: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on track to meet its <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudice to official development assistance.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what “new and additional” means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Currently, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission has taken the year 2009 as a reference: international funding is maintained and 150 million is added in three years as fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers the financing of "all new projects" from 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, no reference is made to previous years' expenditures or to the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, the total amount of France's aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while it pretends to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no standard and everyone chooses the method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that each euro borrowed is equivalent to a donated euro.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often, projects related to the reduction of emissions that are based on more efficient technologies), it is wrong to present a euro that is to be recovered as the equivalent of a euro that is given... At most, only the interest rate of the loan should be calculated for its commitments (the pre-lending country).
But France does not find such reasoning useful: it "respects" its <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million commitment by making 91.5% of loans (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>389.8 million) and 8.5 % of donations (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>36.1 million); see the EU document to see for yourself.
This is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it at 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to meet its commitment, France only contributes ten cents and considers the effort comparable.
That's a good trick!
In short, in its fast-start financing, France performs a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to the actions over time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
Spending just <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>36.1 million, he manages to give the impression that he spends <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million “new and additional”, as he had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has dealt with the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in the negotiations, since developing countries are not fools...
The chapter on early financing is a minor, relatively short-term one, in relation to the whole of the climate negotiations.
But it could be a grain of sand too much in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not the case.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, especially, France could push forward the debates on stakes in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter that is currently being debated): we will not get rid of the question of the "additional character" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its stance to become as progressive on this issue as it is on others.
We therefore have the hope of the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "additional character" and the use of loans would help improve the level of international confidence needed to advance the negotiations.
Warning about pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in one day, according to a study published Wednesday by the Générations Futures association (the former movement for the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have a significant statistical value given the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem," acquired in supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September the foods that a child usually consumes about ten years old in four meals and one snack a day.
These model meals, which follow official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruit and vegetables, three of dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day), as well as treats, were examined in laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The balance of the dish is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, 42 of which are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (PE), according to studies by various institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
“Although, in virtually all cases, the legal limits for each of the chemicals are not exceeded individually, our study clearly shows that consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE contaminants is worrisome,” the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about twenty residues that can harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for the school, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to green jews in Kenya, including in food, where the study has detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, Russian steak, canned tuna and even the bread bar or gum were clad with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the tap water, the analyses found the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon slice was the most “nutritive” with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic dish used to heat the food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The ultimate risk these “contaminant cocktails” pose to the consumer is “probably underestimated,” the study says.
The Europe Ecology-Les Verts Alliance (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "against the gravity of the situation" to implement a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the rise of diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 were in cereals.
